 today the US Securities and Exchange Commission and federal prosecutors ch=
arged him with fraud. Here are the SEC and Department of Justice announceme=
nts. The basic contours of the alleged fraud are pretty simple:=09Left woul=
d sell Company X stock short.=09He would put out a big splashy research rep=
ort, and tweet about it, and go on television, saying =E2=80=9CCompany X is=
 terrible and will go down,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0generally with a price target wel=
l below the current price.=09The market would react to his report/tweet/tel=
evision, and the stock would go down as Citron=E2=80=99s followers shorted =
the stock too.=09Then he=E2=80=99d quickly buy back the stock himself, givi=
ng him (1) a quick profit and (2) no exposure to whether his report was=C2=
=A0right:=C2=A0If it turned out Company X was great and the stock rallied t=
he next day, it didn=E2=80=99t matter to Left, because he had already cover=
ed his short and made money.=09(Also he sometimes went=C2=A0long=C2=A0stock=
s, published bullish reports with high price targets, and then sold quickly=
.)It is so tempting to defend this! Short sellers generally get an undeserv=
ed bad rap, people get mad at them for weak reasons, and of course short se=
llers and journalists are enough alike that I have a soft spot for them.Als=
o,=C2=A0I think, when you lay it out like that, this business model really =
is=C2=A0potentially just fine. Here=E2=80=99s why it=E2=80=99s fine: =E2=80=
=9CFollowing Left=E2=80=99s reports and tweets,=E2=80=9D says the SEC,=C2=
=A0=E2=80=9Cthe price of these target stocks moved on average more than 12%=
.=E2=80=9D That=E2=80=99s a big move! The market read Left=E2=80=99s short =
reports and thought =E2=80=9Coh wow Company X is way worse than I thought, =
I should sell,=E2=80=9D and the stock went down.How could Left have that ef=
fect? The most natural answer is some combination of:=09Investors read his =
reports and tweets, were persuaded by the analysis, and sold the stock. Tha=
t is, his reports were=C2=A0correct. Or,=09Investors just read the headline=
s but thought =E2=80=9Cah, Andrew Left is a good short seller, he=E2=80=99s=
 got a good track record, he took down Valeant, and most of the time when h=
e publishes a short report the stock really is overvalued and goes down ove=
r the long term.=E2=80=9D So even without reading his analysis, investors i=
nterpreted Left=E2=80=99s short report as a strong signal that the stock wo=
uld go down, because of his track record. That is, his reports were=C2=A0co=
rrect, enough of the time, to create and maintain that reputation.These are=
 not the only possible answers. We talk about pump-and-dump schemes a lot a=
round here, in which scammers buy stocks, put out fake but bullish reports =
and then dump the stocks. How do their reports move the stocks? Not by bein=
g right! It=E2=80=99s some combination of (1) the stocks are small and illi=
quid, (2) the scammers trick retail investors into thinking they have a goo=
d track record or inside knowledge or skill and (3) at some level the audie=
nce=C2=A0understands=C2=A0that it=E2=80=99s a pump-and-dump, so they=C2=A0a=
re betting that they=E2=80=99ll be able to sell to a greater fool. Those ar=
e all bad answers. (Probably.)=C2=A0And Left is=C2=A0a big guy on social me=
dia with a retail following, often targeting smallish dicey stocks, so it i=
s possible that he could move stocks using a similar mechanism.
  [1]
But there are reasons to give Left the benefit of the doubt here. He wrote =
reasoned reports. He went after big companies, not just illiquid microcap o=
nes. And he=C2=A0did=C2=A0have a track record:=C2=A0=E2=80=9CA Wall Street =
Journal analysis of 111 Citron short-sale reports published from 2001 to 20=
14 shows an average share-price decline of 42% in the year after a Citron r=
eport was released,=E2=80=9D wrote the Journal=C2=A0in a 2015=C2=A0article =
about his work on Valeant Pharmaceuticals International Inc. I wrote about =
Valeant at the time, and Citron=E2=80=99s work was =E2=80=A6=C2=A0sometimes=
 intemperate =E2=80=A6=C2=A0but largely good, correctly identifying complic=
ated but serious issues at Valeant, not a casual hit job but a serious inve=
stigation.And he has been doing it for a long time. If you put out a flashy=
 report saying =E2=80=9CCompany X is a fraud,=E2=80=9D and it has a lot of =
scandalous details, and you tweet about it a lot, maybe you can move the st=
ock. But then if you turn out to be wrong, people will be disappointed. If =
you do that a few more times, people will stop paying attention. If you wan=
t to do this for the long term =E2=80=94=C2=A0if you want to be able to mov=
e stocks by tweeting about them =E2=80=94=C2=A0you have to care about your =
reputation for accuracy. And Left has been doing it for the long term.But w=
hat about the fact that he covered his shorts soon after publishing his rep=
orts? In theory, I=E2=80=99m not sure it matters. I mean:=09Company X trade=
s at $100.=09Citron determines, correctly, that it is worth $50, and should=
 trade there within a year.=09Citron shorts the stock at $100, then publish=
es a report saying =E2=80=9CCompany X is worth $50.=E2=80=9D=09The market p=
artially digests Citron=E2=80=99s report, and the stock trades to $88 in a =
day.=09Citron can get a 12% one-day return by covering immediately, or can =
wait a year and get a 50% return.The 12% one-day return is probably=C2=A0be=
tter=C2=A0than the 50% one-year return, right? Bigger on an annualized basi=
s, more capital-efficient, more work-efficient (he can stop following Compa=
ny X after taking profits!), less risky. If you do your reports diligently =
and skillfully and honestly, you=E2=80=99ll still be wrong much of the time=
. If the market gives you partial credit for being right=C2=A0every=C2=A0ti=
me, then that=E2=80=99s probably better than waiting to see how the trade w=
ill work out.Citron is in this model a service provider to the market: It=
=C2=A0informs=C2=A0the market that Company X is a fraud, the market saves a=
 lot of money (by not buying Company X at $100 anymore), and Citron gets a =
reasonable cut of the money immediately. Citron is not a long-term investor=
 that has to ride Company X all the way down, and it doesn=E2=80=99t have t=
o make 100% of its profits on any trade contingent on being 100% right abou=
t Company X. In the long run, all of its profits are contingent on being=C2=
=A0right enough=C2=A0about=C2=A0enough=C2=A0of its trades that people keep =
listening to it and prices keep going down.Anyway that is all my abstract d=
efense of Citron Research, the defense that I was more tempted to make befo=
re=C2=A0I read SEC complaint. But then I did and, you know, he doesn=E2=80=
=99t look=C2=A0great. Left seems to be more=C2=A0cynical about this busines=
s model than would be ideal.=C2=A0Now, there is some stuff in here that ove=
rreaches. The SEC=C2=A0criticizes Left for pretending to be a hedge fund ra=
ther than just a guy on Twitter:Defendants posted purported =E2=80=9Cinvest=
or letters=E2=80=9D to create the false impression that Citron Capital was =
a successful hedge fund with investors, when in fact Citron Capital never h=
ad any outside investors and Left simply used Citron Capital to trade his o=
wn money. =E2=80=A6For example, certain investor letters represented that C=
itron Capital managed a =E2=80=9Cpooled investment vehicle=E2=80=9D and ref=
erenced the =E2=80=9CFund=E2=80=99s offering memorandum.=E2=80=9D In additi=
on, in a July 17, 2019 investor letter, Left wrote =E2=80=9Cthe managers of=
 Citron would like to reassure our investors=E2=80=9D when discussing Citro=
n Capital=E2=80=99s trading strategy.I feel like everyone kind of knew that=
 Citron Research was just a guy on Twitter, and =E2=80=9Cthe managers of Ci=
tron would like to reassure our investors=E2=80=9D is the guy-on-Twitter ve=
rsion of the royal =E2=80=9Cwe.=E2=80=9D Sometimes the managers of my 401k =
would like to reassure our investors that we=E2=80=99re doing a good job to=
o, it=E2=80=99s fine.=C2=A0But other stuff is worse. The essential question=
 here is: Did Left honestly try to find companies he thought were bad, shor=
t them, publish=C2=A0his reasoned opinions about why=C2=A0were bad, and the=
n take some risk off the table when the market responded quickly? Or did he=
 just use his fame as a way to make a quick buck, figuring that his reputat=
ion would deteriorate slowly with each bad call, and he could take a lot of=
 money out in the interim?And here the SEC has some pretty suggestive messa=
ges. Left was long one stock, Invitae Corp., and =E2=80=9Cdiscussed with hi=
s colleague his hope to =E2=80=98get stock to 30=E2=80=99 and asked =E2=80=
=98[w]hat can I put in a tweet to juice it[?]=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D Eventually =
he tweeted that he was =E2=80=9Ccertain that Invitae is on its way to $100=
=E2=80=9D and=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cwill continue to stay long until the stock hits=
 at least $65 as we believe it is on its way to $100.=E2=80=9D He sold that=
 day at $27 to $28.Saying =E2=80=9Cwe will continue to stay long until the =
stock hits at least $65=E2=80=9D=C2=A0and then immediately selling at $28=
=C2=A0seems bad, and I can understand why the SEC dislikes it, and it does =
seem=C2=A0dishonest. And it is a recurring theme in this complaint: Left pr=
etty regularly said he was still long (or short) even after taking off most=
 or all of his positions. I am not sure how material this was to investors =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0surely the contents of the report should matter more than hi=
s trading positions? =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it=E2=80=99s a bad look. Closing ou=
t his positions quickly could be fine!
  [2]
 Lying about it is not.But to me even worse=C2=A0is telling his colleague t=
hat he wanted to =E2=80=9Cget stock to 30=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cjuice it.=
=E2=80=9D If you are telling the public about your stock picks, you can=E2=
=80=99t go around saying =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m doing this to get the stock u=
p.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Obviously=C2=A0you are doing it to get the stock up. But y=
ou have to go around saying =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m tweeting stuff about this =
stock because I think it=E2=80=99s true.=E2=80=9D If you are explicitly=C2=
=A0trying to move the stock with public statements, then people will have d=
oubts about whether you mean those statements.Or here are some more unfortu=
nate messages:On August 27, 2018, Left messaged Portfolio Manager One =E2=
=80=9CI have a hot voice in cannibas. Let=E2=80=99s take a vantage [sic] of=
 it.=E2=80=9D Left instructed Portfolio Manager One to not overthink Citron=
 Research=E2=80=99s next target company stating, =E2=80=9CStop being such a=
 pussy. It=E2=80=99s OK to be wrong.=E2=80=9DIt is okay to be wrong! Everyo=
ne gets some calls wrong. But that=E2=80=99s a rough paragraph: If you have=
 a =E2=80=9Chot voice=E2=80=9D and want to =E2=80=9Ctake advantage of it,=
=E2=80=9D and you don=E2=80=99t care too much about being wrong, then that =
suggests the bad story: that Left was=C2=A0using his fame to make a quick b=
uck, rather than publishing research he really believed.That story goes on:=
Left decided to issue a short publication on Cronos Group, a Canadian canna=
bis company that traded on the NASDAQ under the ticker symbol =E2=80=9CCRON=
.=E2=80=9DLeft told Portfolio Manager One =E2=80=9Cwe can DESTROY CRON=E2=
=80=9D and through a =E2=80=9Ccron short we could get 2 bucks,=E2=80=9D ind=
icating he believed that he would make $2 per share from trading around a p=
ublication on CRON.On August 29, 2018, Left had short exposure in CRON, mea=
ning that he would profit if CRON=E2=80=99s stock price decreased. =E2=80=
=A6Later that same day, Left published a report and sent a tweet to his rea=
ders recommending that they sell CRON and that the true valuation of the co=
mpany was $3.50 per share: =E2=80=9C$CRON tgt price $3.5. Everything that i=
s contaminated about the Cannabis space. ALL HYPE with possible securities =
fraud.=E2=80=9D The tweet linked to the report which was titled, =E2=80=9CC=
ronos: The Dark Side of The Cannabis Space.=E2=80=9DAn hour later, Left pos=
ted another tweet to alert his readers that he was going to appear on CNBC =
Fast Money to promote his recommendation: =E2=80=9CAndrew Left from Citron =
on CNBC Fast Money 5:25pm ET to discuss why $CRON is the most overhyped of =
all the =E2=80=98pot stocks=E2=80=99 with a target price of $3.5.=E2=80=9DD=
uring Left=E2=80=99s CNBC interview, the interviewer repeatedly asked him i=
f he continued to hold a short position in CRON: =E2=80=9Cwhat=E2=80=99s re=
levant to people watching is, are you just as short the stock right now as =
you were at the beginning of the day.=E2=80=9D Left responded that he =E2=
=80=9Ctook a small size position off today but I am still extremely short t=
he stock,=E2=80=9D and reiterated his recommendation that the stock would t=
rade to $3.50.This statement was materially false and misleading because, b=
y the time of that interview, Left had exited more than 75% of his short ex=
posure at well above $3.50, despite representing to his readers that this w=
as the true valuation of the company.Left later bragged to Portfolio Manage=
r One that he had received 100 emails on CRON and that =E2=80=9CNOT 1 of th=
em was intelligent . . . . I swear not 1 person with a smart answer not 1=
=E2=80=9D and further bragged that =E2=80=9Ci could write a tweet about a p=
art 2 and get another $1.=E2=80=9DEhhh. It all=C2=A0suggests=C2=A0that the =
positive view of the business model =E2=80=94=C2=A0short stocks you think a=
re bad, publish your best arguments why, and then de-risk promptly but hone=
stly =E2=80=94=C2=A0is not what is going on here.Although! Weirdly the SEC =
does not get into this, but Cronos closed at $12.74 per share on Aug. 29, 2=
018, the day before Left=E2=80=99s report. It closed at $9.12 on Aug. 30, a=
fter the report came out, a 28% drop. It then rallied, getting as high as $=
23.70 in March 2019. But then it mostly went down. It hit Left=E2=80=99s $3=
.50 price target in early 2022, and closed at $2.42 yesterday. It has never=
 reported an operating profit. It took a while, and many readers who shorte=
d the stock presumably lost money, but was Left =E2=80=A6=C2=A0right?In gen=
eral the SEC does not pay much attention to that question.=C2=A0Maybe it is=
 not important? In the government=E2=80=99s telling, Left=C2=A0lied about a=
 lot of stuff =E2=80=94=C2=A0his independence, his credentials, how he got =
paid, and most crucially whether he was still long or short the stocks he w=
as writing about =E2=80=94=C2=A0that probably=C2=A0was=C2=A0material to his=
 readers, and if he had been more honest about those things he might have m=
oved the stocks less. He made money through dishonesty, the government alle=
ges, and that=E2=80=99s probably enough for their case.But the government s=
ays less about the=C2=A0central=C2=A0things he said to the public: =E2=80=
=9CThis stock is good=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cthat stock is bad.=E2=80=9D
  [3]
 If he=C2=A0believed those things based on real research, and was mostly co=
rrect, then he would have a pretty good argument that it wasn=E2=80=99t=C2=
=A0really fraud, even if he was dishonest about his own positions and cynic=
al about his audience. If he was just making stuff up to manipulate stocks,=
 on the other hand, there=E2=80=99s not much defense.=C2=A0If you'd like to=
 get=C2=A0Money=C2=A0Stuff=C2=A0in handy email form, right in your inbox, p=
lease=C2=A0subscribe at this link. Or you can subscribe to Money Stuff and =
other great Bloomberg newsletters here. Thanks!
