<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Citron</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The thing is, part of me wants to take=
 Andrew Left=E2=80=99s side here. Left is an activist short seller who publ=
ishes reports as Citron Research, and today the US Securities and Exchange =
Commission and federal prosecutors <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbu=
siness.com/click/36208872.193392/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2=
FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDctMjYvc2VjLXN1ZXMtYW5kcmV3LWxlZnQtY2l0cm9uLWNhcGl0YWwtb=
3Zlci1zdG9jay1zaG9ydC1zZWxsaW5nP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA3MjcyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9t=
ZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDcyNyZ1dG1fY2F=
tcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1850f40e" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">charged =
him with fraud</a>. Here are the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/36208872.193392/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzcm9vbS9wcmVz=
cy1yZWxlYXNlcy8yMDI0LTg5/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa9243dbd" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">SEC</a>=
 and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/36208872.1933=
92/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuanVzdGljZS5nb3Yvb3BhL3ByL2FjdGl2aXN0LXNob3J0LXNlbGxlci1j=
aGFyZ2VkLTE2bS1zdG9jay1tYXJrZXQtbWFuaXB1bGF0aW9uLXNjaGVtZQ/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cB2b5f29a9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D=
"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;">Department of Justice</a> announcements. The bas=
ic contours of the alleged fraud are pretty simple:</p><ol style=3D"list-st=
yle-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"mar=
gin-bottom: 5px;">Left would sell Company X stock short.</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">He would put out a big splashy research report, an=
d tweet about it, and go on television, saying =E2=80=9CCompany X is terrib=
le and will go down,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0generally with a price target well below=
 the current price.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The market wou=
ld react to his report/tweet/television, and the stock would go down as Cit=
ron=E2=80=99s followers shorted the stock too.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-b=
ottom: 5px;">Then he=E2=80=99d quickly buy back the stock himself, giving h=
im (1) a quick profit and (2) no exposure to whether his report was=C2=A0<e=
m>right:=C2=A0</em>If it turned out Company X was great and the stock ralli=
ed the next day, it didn=E2=80=99t matter to Left, because he had already c=
overed his short and made money.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">(=
Also he sometimes went=C2=A0<em>long=C2=A0</em>stocks, published bullish re=
ports with high price targets, and then sold quickly.)</li></ol><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">It is so tempting to defend this! Short sellers generally=
 get an undeserved bad rap, people get mad at them for weak reasons, and of=
 course short sellers and journalists are enough alike that I have a soft s=
pot for them.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also,=C2=A0I think, when you =
lay it out like that, this business model really is=C2=A0<em>potentially ju=
st fine</em>. Here=E2=80=99s why it=E2=80=99s fine: =E2=80=9CFollowing Left=
=E2=80=99s reports and tweets,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/36208872.193392/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9maWxlcy9sa=
XRpZ2F0aW9uL2NvbXBsYWludHMvMjAyNC9jb21wLXByMjAyNC04OS5wZGY/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cB95956e28" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D=
"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;">says the SEC</a>,=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cthe price of the=
se target stocks moved on average more than 12%.=E2=80=9D That=E2=80=99s a =
big move! The market read Left=E2=80=99s short reports and thought =E2=80=
=9Coh wow Company X is way worse than I thought, I should sell,=E2=80=9D an=
d the stock went down.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">How could Left have =
that effect? The most natural answer is some combination of:</p><ul style=
=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li styl=
e=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Investors read his reports and tweets, were persu=
aded by the analysis, and sold the stock. That is, his reports were=C2=A0<e=
m>correct</em>. Or,</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Investors just=
 read the headlines but thought =E2=80=9Cah, Andrew Left is a good short se=
ller, he=E2=80=99s got a good track record, he took down Valeant, and most =
of the time when he publishes a short report the stock really is overvalued=
 and goes down over the long term.=E2=80=9D So even without reading his ana=
lysis, investors interpreted Left=E2=80=99s short report as a strong signal=
 that the stock would go down, because of his track record. That is, his re=
ports were=C2=A0<em>correct</em>, enough of the time, to create and maintai=
n that reputation.</li></ul><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These are not the =
only possible answers. We talk about <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/36208872.193392/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGlu=
aW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDctMDEvcHVtcC1hbmQtZHVtcC1hbmQtcHVsbC10aGUtcnVnP2N=
tcGlkPUJCRDA3MjcyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZX=
dzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDcyNyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cBd4cc5d53" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;">pump-and-dump schemes</a> a lot around her=
e, in which scammers buy stocks, put out fake but bullish reports and then =
dump the stocks. How do their reports move the stocks? Not by being right! =
It=E2=80=99s some combination of (1) the stocks are small and illiquid, (2)=
 the scammers trick retail investors into thinking they have a good track r=
ecord or inside knowledge or skill and (3) at some level the audience=C2=A0=
<em>understands=C2=A0</em>that it=E2=80=99s a pump-and-dump, so they=C2=A0a=
re betting that they=E2=80=99ll be able to sell to a greater fool. Those ar=
e all bad answers. (<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/clic=
k/36208872.193392/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzL=
zIwMjQtMDMtMjEvcHVtcC1hbmQtZHVtcHMtYXJlLWxlZ2FsLW5vdz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNzI3MjRf=
TU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGV=
ybT0yNDA3MjcmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5ddce=
89b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">Probably</a>.)=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And Left =
is=C2=A0a big guy on social media with a retail following, often targeting =
smallish dicey stocks, so it is possible that he could move stocks using a =
similar mechanism.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D=
"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px=
; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backg=
round-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But there are reasons to give Left the=
 benefit of the doubt here. He wrote reasoned reports. He went after big co=
mpanies, not just illiquid microcap ones. And he=C2=A0<em>did=C2=A0</em>hav=
e a track record:=C2=A0=E2=80=9CA Wall Street Journal analysis of 111 Citro=
n short-sale reports published from 2001 to 2014 shows an average share-pri=
ce decline of 42% in the year after a Citron report was released,=E2=80=9D =
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/36208872.193392/aH=
R0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy90aGUtc2hvcnQtd2hvLXNhbmstdmFsZWFudC1zd=
G9jay0xNDQ1NTU3MTU3/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBef43b5ee" itemprop=3D"StoryLin=
k" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-=
decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color:=
 #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">wrote the Jo=
urnal</a>=C2=A0in a 2015=C2=A0article about his work on Valeant Pharmaceuti=
cals International Inc. I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/36208872.193392/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGl=
jbGVzLzIwMTUtMTAtMjYvdmFsZWFudC1zLXBoYXJtYWN5LXJlbGF0aW9uc2hpcHMtd2VyZS1jb2=
1wbGljYXRlZD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNzI3MjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0b=
V9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDA3MjcmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1=
ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB55aefdfd" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">wrote about Valeant</a> at t=
he time, and Citron=E2=80=99s work was =E2=80=A6=C2=A0sometimes intemperate=
 =E2=80=A6=C2=A0but largely good, correctly identifying complicated but ser=
ious issues at Valeant, not a casual hit job but a serious investigation.</=
p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And he has been doing it for a long time. If=
 you put out a flashy report saying =E2=80=9CCompany X is a fraud,=E2=80=9D=
 and it has a lot of scandalous details, and you tweet about it a lot, mayb=
e you can move the stock. But then if you turn out to be wrong, people will=
 be disappointed. If you do that a few more times, people will stop paying =
attention. If you want to do this for the long term =E2=80=94=C2=A0if you w=
ant to be able to move stocks by tweeting about them =E2=80=94=C2=A0you hav=
e to care about your reputation for accuracy. And Left has been doing it fo=
r the long term.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But what about the fact th=
at he covered his shorts soon after publishing his reports? <em>In theory</=
em>, I=E2=80=99m not sure it matters. I mean:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-ty=
pe: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bo=
ttom: 5px;">Company X trades at $100.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5p=
x;">Citron determines, correctly, that it is worth $50, and should trade th=
ere within a year.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Citron shorts t=
he stock at $100, then publishes a report saying =E2=80=9CCompany X is wort=
h $50.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The market partial=
ly digests Citron=E2=80=99s report, and the stock trades to $88 in a day.</=
li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Citron can get a 12% one-day return=
 by covering immediately, or can wait a year and get a 50% return.</li></ol=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The 12% one-day return is probably=C2=A0<em>b=
etter=C2=A0</em>than the 50% one-year return, right? Bigger on an annualize=
d basis, more capital-efficient, more work-efficient (he can stop following=
 Company X after taking profits!), less risky. If you do your reports dilig=
ently and skillfully and honestly, you=E2=80=99ll still be wrong much of th=
e time. If the market gives you partial credit for being right=C2=A0<em>eve=
ry=C2=A0</em>time, then that=E2=80=99s probably better than waiting to see =
how the trade will work out.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Citron is in t=
his model a service provider to the market: It=C2=A0<em>informs=C2=A0</em>t=
he market that Company X is a fraud, the market saves a lot of money (by no=
t buying Company X at $100 anymore), and Citron gets a reasonable cut of th=
e money immediately. Citron is not a long-term investor that has to ride Co=
mpany X all the way down, and it doesn=E2=80=99t have to make 100% of its p=
rofits on any trade contingent on being 100% right about Company X. In the =
long run, all of its profits are contingent on being=C2=A0<em>right enough=
=C2=A0</em>about=C2=A0<em>enough=C2=A0</em>of its trades that people keep l=
istening to it and prices keep going down.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
Anyway that is all my abstract defense of Citron Research, the defense that=
 I was more tempted to make before=C2=A0I read SEC complaint. But then I di=
d and, you know, he doesn=E2=80=99t look=C2=A0<em>great</em>. Left seems to=
 be more=C2=A0cynical about this business model than would be ideal.=C2=A0N=
ow, there is some stuff in here that overreaches. The SEC=C2=A0criticizes L=
eft for pretending to be a hedge fund rather than just a guy on Twitter:</p=
><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Defendants posted purported =E2=
=80=9Cinvestor letters=E2=80=9D to create the false impression that Citron =
Capital was a successful hedge fund with investors, when in fact Citron Cap=
ital never had any outside investors and Left simply used Citron Capital to=
 trade his own money. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For example=
, certain investor letters represented that Citron Capital managed a =E2=80=
=9Cpooled investment vehicle=E2=80=9D and referenced the =E2=80=9CFund=E2=
=80=99s offering memorandum.=E2=80=9D In addition, in a July 17, 2019 inves=
tor letter, Left wrote =E2=80=9Cthe managers of Citron would like to reassu=
re our investors=E2=80=9D when discussing Citron Capital=E2=80=99s trading =
strategy.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I feel like everyone=
 kind of knew that Citron Research was just a guy on Twitter, and =E2=80=9C=
the managers of Citron would like to reassure our investors=E2=80=9D is the=
 guy-on-Twitter version of the royal =E2=80=9Cwe.=E2=80=9D Sometimes the ma=
nagers of my 401k would like to reassure our investors that we=E2=80=99re d=
oing a good job too, it=E2=80=99s fine.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">But other stuff is worse. The essential question here is: Did Left hones=
tly try to find companies he thought were bad, short them, publish=C2=A0his=
 reasoned opinions about why=C2=A0were bad, and then take some risk off the=
 table when the market responded quickly? Or did he just use his fame as a =
way to make a quick buck, figuring that his reputation would deteriorate sl=
owly with each bad call, and he could take a lot of money out in the interi=
m?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And here the SEC has some pretty suggest=
ive messages. Left was long one stock, Invitae Corp., and =E2=80=9Cdiscusse=
d with his colleague his hope to =E2=80=98get stock to 30=E2=80=99 and aske=
d =E2=80=98[w]hat can I put in a tweet to juice it[?]=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D Eve=
ntually he tweeted that he was =E2=80=9Ccertain that Invitae is on its way =
to $100=E2=80=9D and=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cwill continue to stay long until the sto=
ck hits at least $65 as we believe it is on its way to $100.=E2=80=9D He so=
ld that day at $27 to $28.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Saying =E2=80=9C=
we will continue to stay long until the stock hits at least $65=E2=80=9D=C2=
=A0and then immediately selling at $28=C2=A0<em>seems bad</em>, and I can u=
nderstand why the SEC dislikes it, and it does seem=C2=A0dishonest. And it =
is a recurring theme in this complaint: Left pretty regularly said he was s=
till long (or short) even after taking off most or all of his positions. I =
am not sure how material this was to investors =E2=80=94=C2=A0surely the co=
ntents of the report should matter more than his trading positions? =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0but it=E2=80=99s a bad <em>look</em>. Closing out his positions qu=
ickly could be fine!<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; ba=
ckground-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a> Lying about it is not.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But to me even =
worse=C2=A0is telling his colleague that he wanted to =E2=80=9Cget stock to=
 30=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cjuice it.=E2=80=9D If you are telling the public =
about your stock picks, you can=E2=80=99t go around saying =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=
=99m doing this to get the stock up.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0<em>Obviously=C2=A0</em>=
you are doing it to get the stock up. But you have to go around saying =E2=
=80=9CI=E2=80=99m tweeting stuff about this stock because I think it=E2=80=
=99s true.=E2=80=9D If you are explicitly=C2=A0trying to move the stock wit=
h public statements, then people will have doubts about whether you mean th=
ose statements.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or here are some more unfor=
tunate messages:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On August 27, =
2018, Left messaged Portfolio Manager One =E2=80=9C<em>I have a hot voice i=
n cannibas. Let=E2=80=99s take a vantage [sic] of it</em>.=E2=80=9D Left in=
structed Portfolio Manager One to not overthink Citron Research=E2=80=99s n=
ext target company stating, =E2=80=9C<em>Stop being such a pussy. It=E2=80=
=99s OK to be wrong.</em>=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">It is okay to be wrong! Everyone gets some calls wrong. But that=E2=80=
=99s a rough paragraph: If you have a =E2=80=9Chot voice=E2=80=9D and want =
to =E2=80=9Ctake advantage of it,=E2=80=9D and you don=E2=80=99t care too m=
uch about being wrong, then that suggests the bad story: that Left was=C2=
=A0using his fame to make a quick buck, rather than publishing research he =
really believed.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That story goes on:</p><bl=
ockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Left decided to issue a short publica=
tion on Cronos Group, a Canadian cannabis company that traded on the NASDAQ=
 under the ticker symbol =E2=80=9CCRON.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">Left told Portfolio Manager One =E2=80=9C<em>we can DESTROY CRON</em>=
=E2=80=9D and through a =E2=80=9C<em>cron short we could get 2 bucks</em>,=
=E2=80=9D indicating he believed that he would make $2 per share from tradi=
ng around a publication on CRON.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On August =
29, 2018, Left had short exposure in CRON, meaning that he would profit if =
CRON=E2=80=99s stock price decreased. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">Later that same day, Left published a report and sent a tweet to his r=
eaders recommending that they sell CRON and that the true valuation of the =
company was $3.50 per share: =E2=80=9C<em>$CRON tgt price $3.5. Everything =
that is contaminated about the Cannabis space. ALL HYPE with possible secur=
ities fraud</em>.=E2=80=9D The tweet linked to the report which was titled,=
 =E2=80=9C<em>Cronos: The Dark Side of The Cannabis Space.</em>=E2=80=9D</p=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">An hour later, Left posted another tweet to a=
lert his readers that he was going to appear on CNBC Fast Money to promote =
his recommendation: =E2=80=9C<em>Andrew Left from Citron on CNBC Fast Money=
 5:25pm ET to discuss why $CRON is the most overhyped of all the =E2=80=98p=
ot stocks=E2=80=99 with a target price of $3.5</em>.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">During Left=E2=80=99s CNBC interview, the interviewer =
repeatedly asked him if he continued to hold a short position in CRON: =E2=
=80=9C<em>what=E2=80=99s relevant to people watching is, are you just as sh=
ort the stock right now as you were at the beginning of the day.</em>=E2=80=
=9D Left responded that he =E2=80=9C<em>took a small size position off toda=
y but I am still extremely short the stock</em>,=E2=80=9D and reiterated hi=
s recommendation that the stock would trade to $3.50.</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">This statement was materially false and misleading because, by t=
he time of that interview, Left had exited more than 75% of his short expos=
ure at well above $3.50, despite representing to his readers that this was =
the true valuation of the company.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Left lat=
er bragged to Portfolio Manager One that he had received 100 emails on CRON=
 and that =E2=80=9C<em>NOT 1 of them was intelligent . . . . I swear not 1 =
person with a smart answer not 1</em>=E2=80=9D and further bragged that =E2=
=80=9C<em>i could write a tweet about a part 2 and get another $1.</em>=E2=
=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ehhh. It all=C2=A0<em>s=
uggests=C2=A0</em>that the positive view of the business model =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0short stocks you think are bad, publish your best arguments why, and the=
n de-risk promptly but honestly =E2=80=94=C2=A0is not what is going on here=
.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Although! Weirdly the SEC does not get in=
to this, but Cronos closed at $12.74 per share on Aug. 29, 2018, the day be=
fore Left=E2=80=99s report. It closed at $9.12 on Aug. 30, after the report=
 came out, a 28% drop. It then rallied, getting as high as $23.70 in March =
2019. But then it mostly went down. It hit Left=E2=80=99s $3.50 price targe=
t in early 2022, and closed at $2.42 yesterday. It has never reported an op=
erating profit. It took a while, and many readers who shorted the stock pre=
sumably lost money, but was Left =E2=80=A6=C2=A0right?</p><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">In general the SEC does not pay much attention to that question=
.=C2=A0Maybe it is not important? In the government=E2=80=99s telling, Left=
=C2=A0lied about a lot of stuff =E2=80=94=C2=A0his independence, his creden=
tials, how he got paid, and most crucially whether he was still long or sho=
rt the stocks he was writing about =E2=80=94=C2=A0that probably=C2=A0<em>wa=
s=C2=A0</em>material to his readers, and if he had been more honest about t=
hose things he might have moved the stocks less. He made money through dish=
onesty, the government alleges, and that=E2=80=99s probably enough for thei=
r case.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the government says less about =
the=C2=A0<em>central=C2=A0</em>things he said to the public: =E2=80=9CThis =
stock is good=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cthat stock is bad.=E2=80=9D<a class=3D"=
footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !impo=
rtant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a> If he=C2=A0<em>believed</em> those things based on real research, and =
was mostly <em>correct</em>, then he would have a pretty good argument that=
 it wasn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>really</em> fraud, even if he was dishonest abo=
ut his own positions and cynical about his audience. If he was just making =
stuff up to manipulate stocks, on the other hand, there=E2=80=99s not much =
defense.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><span class=3D"news-designed=
-for-consumer-media"><em>If you'd like to get=C2=A0Money=C2=A0Stuff=C2=A0in=
 handy email form, right in your inbox, please=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link=
.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/36208872.193392/aHR0cDovL2xpbmsubWFpbC5ib=
G9vbWJlcmdidXNpbmVzcy5jb20vam9pbi80d20vbW9uZXlzdHVmZi1zaWdudXAmaGFzaD01NDIy=
MzAwMWNhM2ZmY2Y0MGYyNjI5YzI1YWNlYTY3YQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB41f24786" t=
arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;">subscribe at this link</a>. Or you can s=
ubscribe to Money Stuff and other great Bloomberg newsletters <a href=3D"ht=
tps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/36208872.193392/aHR0cHM6Ly9sb2d=
pbi5ibG9vbWJlcmcuY29tL25ld3NsZXR0ZXJz/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBdd55da8a" it=
emprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-=
decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color:=
 #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">here</a>. Th=
anks!</em></span></p>
